@node intro "Introduction - What and why"

 Introduction
 ------------

AVB is a short program I wrote while trying to incorporate sound effects
into an animation I had produced.  I found a few solutions on Aminet, some
particularly elegant such as AGMS, but none that did quite what I wanted.
( Keeping file overheads small ) I had an old program supplied with
Sculpt4D, but that refused to work with KickStart 3.0.  ( I only discovered
YAFA after writing this program )

@endnode

@node install "AVB Installation"

 Installation
 ------------

AVB  can  be  installed anywhere, and requires no libraries, fonts or other
such files to work. ( yet )

C:  would be a good place for it, as would anywhere else in your path.

@endnode

@node usage "How to use AVB"

 AVB Usage
 ---------

For AVB to play sound together with an animation, you have to write two
files using a normal text editor, that tell AVB when to play a sound, and
what sound to play.  ( Labelled [filename].trk and [filename].snd
respectively ).  Lets say you have an animation called "WZIntro" which
involves an armoured car blowing up a tank with a missle, and you want to
choreograph sound with the anim.  ( Interestingly enough, such an animation
exists and is part of the intro to a game being written by a friend of mine
at the moment.  )

You'd create a file called "WZIntro.snd" which looks like this...

Data:Samples/Weapons/Laser07
Data:Samples/Weapons/Boom07
Data:Samples/Mechanical/CarSkid1

Fairly simple stuff, this file tells AVB to load the IFF sound called
"Laser07" into sound slot one, "Boom07" into sound slot two etc.  The sound
files MUST be IFF-8SVX to work, and the correct paths must be specified.
You can use assigns as part of the filename.

Then create a file called "WZIntro.trk" which looks like this...

020003
044001
054001
064001
074001
084001
085001
095002

Each line holds a frame number, and a sound slot number together as a six
digit number.  So the first line tells AVB to play the sound in slot 003 at
frame number 020 of the animation, so it would play the CarSkid1 sample.
The second says play sound slot 001 at frame number 044, which is a laser
cannon firing.  And at frame 095 the tank gets shot and destroyed, so sound
slot 002, which is an explosion, is played.

Each line must contain the data stored as shown, the frame number as three
digits, and the sound slot number as three digits.

The frames do not have to be in order, so the following .trk file is
perfectly legal.

020003
064001
085001
084001
095002
074001
054001
044001

   Playing the animation
   ---------------------

*********************************************************************
@{b}(Warning: AVB loads the sound data and animation data into Chip ram in
version 1.0b.  Make sure you have enough ram for all the data!!!)@{ub}
*********************************************************************

To run the animation with sound, once you've written the .trk and .snd
files, put them all into the same drawer, CD to that directory and type

AVB [filename]

(Assuming AVB is in your path somewhere.) If the animation is a HAM
animation, use this instead...

AVB [filename] -h

Otherwise the anim wont come out quite right.

AVB will quit as soon as the animation has finished.

@endnode

@node history "History of AVB..."

 History
 -------

AVB History.

September 20, 1996   :V0.01

   First coding.

September 21, 1996   :V0.5

   Main coding complete, but sound data was hard coded into program.
   Attempts at x2 pixels realtime failed miserably. :)

September 22, 1996   :V0.9

   Sound data input via ascii text files for ease of use.  AVB crashes if
   it can't find the sound files specified.  Wrote up history, buglist, and
   todo lists.

September 25, 1996   :V1.0b

   AVB no longer crashes if it cannot find the data files associated with
the animation. ie the support files or the sound samples. Added
comprehensive error checking routines.

September 29, 1996   :V1.0b

   AVB V1.0b is sent to the support BBS for testing.

September 30, 1996   :V1.0b

   Guide file created for AVB by Kenji Irie

@endnode

